09:42.800 --> 09:46.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would suspect the
congressional investigating
committee and the special
counsel will continue

09:48.933 --> 09:52.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to dig into questions raised
by the facts disclosed by The
New York Times and by Donald

09:53.266 --> 09:55.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Trump Jr. himself.

09:55.233 --> 09:59.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But this is highly suggestive
of a potential violation
of the law on two counts.

09:59.166 --> 10:04.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Number one, it demonstrates
that the campaign as a whole
had the intent to court support,

10:06.100 --> 10:10.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
receive support, solicit
support from a foreign national
source, in this case, the Russia

10:10.366 --> 10:12.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
government.

10:12.366 --> 10:16.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Second, in my view, the
meeting itself could constitute
illegal solicitation of support

10:17.766 --> 10:19.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from a foreign national
under campaign finance law.

10:19.833 --> 10:24.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it both has broad legal
significance, and on that one
specific issue of liability,

10:24.400 --> 10:26.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
has a more concrete
significance.

10:26.400 --> 10:31.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, you're
tying it to campaign
finance, is that right?

10:31.200 --> 10:33.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
BOB BAUER: Yes.

10:33.166 --> 10:36.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm talking here about a statute
that has been on the books
for many years that Congress

10:36.266 --> 10:41.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tightened in 2002 that prohibits
receiving and soliciting
contributions from a foreign

10:44.000 --> 10:48.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
national or providing
the foreign national with
substantial assistance
in trying to influence

10:48.433 --> 10:50.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a U.S. election.

10:50.500 --> 10:53.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Jed Shugerman,
listening to this, and I
know you have been looking at

10:53.800 --> 10:58.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the laws with regard to this
today, does this sound like
something that fits under that

10:59.566 --> 11:01.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
legal definition?

11:01.700 --> 11:02.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JED SHUGERMAN, Fordham
University Law School:
Yes, I have been looking
at this quite a bit

11:02.900 --> 11:04.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and I have been
reading Bob's work.

11:04.366 --> 11:06.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And Bob is -- generally, he's
a terrific expert on this.

11:06.933 --> 11:11.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I think I disagree with
him and how far to apply
campaign finance law.

11:11.400 --> 11:14.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I'm very sympathetic to
his perspective here.

11:14.700 --> 11:19.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, I think we're
getting into some dangerous
territory with applying
federal election law

11:20.566 --> 11:22.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
too broadly at this stage.

11:22.633 --> 11:26.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
News keeps breaking every day,
so I'm just saying, what we
know now, to argue that this

11:26.233 --> 11:31.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
meeting itself is a violation
of the campaign finance law
raises a couple of questions.

11:33.233 --> 11:37.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
First of all, it raises
the danger of applying
and criminalizing
contacts between anyone

11:39.733 --> 11:42.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in a campaign with
a foreign national.

11:42.000 --> 11:44.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Let me give you a hypothetical.

11:44.066 --> 11:48.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Imagine if there was a Web site
that published what purported
to be the birth certificate

11:50.466 --> 11:54.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of President Obama from Kenya,
and an Obama staffer went
and met with Kenyan nationals

11:56.266 --> 12:00.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to find out about the
veracity of that document.

12:00.400 --> 12:05.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Under this interpretation,
that would still be a thing of
value, but would we criminalize

12:05.133 --> 12:07.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Obama campaign for checking?

12:07.400 --> 12:12.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, similarly, would we say
of the Romney campaign, you
can't do opposition research

12:12.366 --> 12:13.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
by investigating?

12:13.366 --> 12:14.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

12:14.366 --> 12:16.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JED SHUGERMAN: Yes, go ahead.

12:16.366 --> 12:18.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I was just
going to say, let me just
stop you there on that point.

12:18.400 --> 12:22.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What about that, Bob Bauer,
that there's a danger here
in making this cover any kind

12:23.933 --> 12:26.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of information that is
shared with a campaign
by a foreign entity?

12:26.400 --> 12:29.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BOB BAUER: Well, that's
not the case at all here.

12:29.766 --> 12:34.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're not talking about a
casual conversation with some
information that the campaign is

12:36.400 --> 12:39.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
looking for it sort
of acquires by talking
to a foreign national.

12:39.100 --> 12:44.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We're talking about an
operational link between
a foreign government
and a campaign, one in

12:46.100 --> 12:49.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which the foreign government is
stating its intention to provide
ongoing support, dispatches

12:49.066 --> 12:54.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one of its emissaries, if we're
to understand the facts as
so far presented in the news,

12:55.566 --> 12:58.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dispatches one of its emissaries
from Moscow to Washington, D.C.

12:58.600 --> 13:02.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And on top of all that, not
only does the campaign indicate
that it's anxious for the

13:02.766 --> 13:07.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
help, but, as you recall,
Donald Trump Jr. even suggests
in one of his e-mails that he

13:07.166 --> 13:10.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would like to discuss timing,
that if the information is as
good as advertised, he would

13:10.933 --> 13:13.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
like to see it released
later in the summer.

13:13.166 --> 13:18.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The campaign finance
laws clearly distinguish
between the kind of
speech that I think that

13:20.233 --> 13:23.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Professor Shugerman is
legitimately concerned
about from this kind of
operational relationship

13:25.566 --> 13:27.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by a strong supporter
for a campaign engaged
in very specific
activities on its behalf.

13:27.733 --> 13:32.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Jed Shugerman,
it is the case that the e-mail
to Donald Trump Jr. said the

13:34.600 --> 13:37.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Russian government wants
to help your campaign.

13:37.700 --> 13:42.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JED SHUGERMAN: All of this is
indicative or suggestive of
what we might find out later.

13:44.666 --> 13:48.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think if we carefully read
the e-mails, I think it's hard
to make the leap that this

13:48.766 --> 13:50.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is like a coordination.

13:50.000 --> 13:51.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's indications there.

13:51.666 --> 13:53.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I understand where Bob
Bauer is coming from.

13:53.866 --> 13:58.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think we have to be
careful, though, because if you
read the e-mail from a little

13:58.266 --> 14:02.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bit of perspective of how could
this be applied in the future
and can we have line-drawing

14:02.933 --> 14:07.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
here, it's hard to see where
this e-mail doesn't lead to some
effect of applying this to any

14:09.400 --> 14:11.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
kind of contact
between a government...

14:11.433 --> 14:13.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let me
now ask both of you.

14:13.333 --> 14:15.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And I will come to you,
Jed Shugerman first.

14:15.433 --> 14:20.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The word collusion, colluding
has been thrown around a lot in
the last few weeks about whether

14:21.633 --> 14:25.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Trump campaign was colluding
with Russian officials.

14:25.200 --> 14:28.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Is there some legal
connection there?

14:28.066 --> 14:30.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that an issue?

14:30.100 --> 14:32.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JED SHUGERMAN: Well,
the word collusion is
more of a political
word than a legal word.

14:32.933 --> 14:35.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
There is no statute
against collusion.

14:35.600 --> 14:38.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And -- but I think the
word we might turn to in
the law is conspiracy.

14:38.833 --> 14:40.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is where we're headed.

14:40.766 --> 14:44.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there is a lot of other
information that is coming
out day by day that points

14:45.566 --> 14:47.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to this conspiracy.

14:47.333 --> 14:49.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we may have conspiracy.

14:49.333 --> 14:53.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think what we're getting
closer towards is a violation
of 1986 law of computer hacking,

14:55.633 --> 14:58.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because I think, if you look
at the timing, there are just
too many coincidences about

14:58.100 --> 15:02.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what the Trump campaign was
doing before and after this June
3 e-mail about President Trump

15:02.633 --> 15:04.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
himself.

15:04.633 --> 15:08.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I just -- my point here is,
I think we need to be careful
in analyzing each step.

15:09.366 --> 15:11.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

15:11.433 --> 15:13.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JED SHUGERMAN: I think there is
evidence that's pointing towards
crimes, but I think we need

15:13.200 --> 15:16.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to be careful when we
make interpretations
of these statutes.

15:16.400 --> 15:18.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well,
we certainly want
to be careful here.

15:18.433 --> 15:23.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we know we're speculating,
but we do think it's important
to ask these questions.

15:23.266 --> 15:26.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bob Bauer, just quickly on
the conspiracy question?

15:26.066 --> 15:29.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
BOB BAUER: Well, I think
there is a basis here.

15:29.166 --> 15:31.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I don't disagree
with Professor Shugerman.

15:31.400 --> 15:33.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This is going to be an
ongoing investigation.

15:33.166 --> 15:36.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is not the only evidence
that will be taken into account.

15:36.466 --> 15:41.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And certainly, if, in fact,
there is apparently a violation
of the campaign finance laws,

15:43.433 --> 15:46.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and the evidence is beginning
to point in that direction,
then, yes, the prosecutors

15:46.500 --> 15:50.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
could certainly develop a
conspiracy charge or an aiding
and abetting charge based on

15:50.933 --> 15:53.066 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

15:53.066 --> 15:56.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If I could just add one more
point, this is not a statute
that is subject to the same

15:56.766 --> 16:01.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
free speech considerations that
Professor Shugerman outlines
that apply in the domestic

16:01.300 --> 16:03.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
U.S. context.

16:03.366 --> 16:07.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today, for example, it was
very clear from the testimony
of FBI director nominee Chris

16:09.233 --> 16:12.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Wray, who was asked about this,
that, in his view, this sort
of communication between the

16:12.100 --> 16:15.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russian government
and a campaign is a
national security matter.

16:15.866 --> 16:20.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he said any meeting
like that shouldn't have
been taken unless the
campaign had consulted

16:20.266 --> 16:22.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with what he called
its legal advisers.

16:22.500 --> 16:27.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, I think it was clear
from the FBI director's
remarks here this is a
national security issue,

16:29.333 --> 16:31.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the free speech considerations
are different, and the
implications are legal.

16:31.433 --> 16:34.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right,
gentlemen, we are going
to have to leave it there.

16:34.100 --> 16:36.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bob Bauer, Jed Shugerman,
we thank you both.

16:36.633 --> 16:37.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BOB BAUER: Thanks for having us.

16:37.800 --> 16:41.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JED SHUGERMAN:
Thank you very much.

16:41.766 --> 16:46.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: As we noted
earlier, the issue of Russian
meddling figured into the Senate

16:52.300 --> 16:57.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
confirmation hearing today for
Christopher Wray, the nominee
to be the next FBI director.

16:58.466 --> 17:00.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But it was not the
only topic of note.

17:00.900 --> 17:04.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Senators were also trying to
