anticipated for months.

21:27.900 --> 21:32.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Finally, some time between
Monday and today, the Larsen
Sea Ice Shelf became 12 percent

21:34.866 --> 21:36.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
smaller.

21:36.366 --> 21:38.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we have known about this
for quite a while, right?

21:38.433 --> 21:40.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
KELLY BRUNT, University
of Maryland: We have
certainly known about
the bulk of this rift

21:40.966 --> 21:43.066 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for a while.

21:43.066 --> 21:46.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Kelly Brunt is a
glaciologist at the University
of Maryland and NASA's Goddard

21:46.566 --> 21:48.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Space Flight Center.

21:48.666 --> 21:53.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She used a wall of monitors
there to show me the growing
rift, fueled in part by rising

21:54.566 --> 21:56.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
air and sea temperatures.

21:56.666 --> 22:01.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If the glaciers in West
Antarctica all dropped
into the water, global
sea level would rise

22:02.266 --> 22:04.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
by more than 15 feet.

22:04.500 --> 22:09.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Brunt showed me the big
picture, a composite of images
from several satellites.

22:10.566 --> 22:12.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This is how the
glacier ice flows here.

22:12.700 --> 22:17.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KELLY BRUNT: Ice flows from
the center of the continent
out to the edges, much like

22:19.200 --> 22:21.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
syrup on the center of
your pancake flowing
towards the edges.

22:21.200 --> 22:24.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you can see there are
areas where it's moving pretty
slowly, and then there are areas

22:24.700 --> 22:27.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
where it's moving very quickly.

22:27.066 --> 22:31.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And those quick places
are generally in our
areas of ice shelves.

22:31.200 --> 22:34.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So, when we
think about ice, we think
about something static.

22:34.466 --> 22:35.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not static, is it?

22:35.466 --> 22:36.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KELLY BRUNT: Not at all.

22:36.533 --> 22:38.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Actually, it's highly dynamic.

22:38.466 --> 22:42.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You can see from this
image it looks to me a
lot like a river system.

22:42.800 --> 22:47.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Ice shelves
are connected to the glaciers
that sit on land, but they are

22:49.266 --> 22:51.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
also floating, like ice
cubes in a glass of water.

22:51.566 --> 22:56.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KELLY BRUNT: If you had a drink
with ice cubes in it, as those
ice cube melts, they don't

22:56.433 --> 23:00.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
add to the height of
the water in the glass.

23:00.866 --> 23:05.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So when ice shelves break down
and collapse, they do not have
a direct impact on mean sea

23:07.033 --> 23:08.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
level rise.

23:08.266 --> 23:10.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
However, they have
an indirect effect.

23:10.300 --> 23:14.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These ice shelves buttress
the flow of the ice upstream,
the ice that's flowing into

23:15.500 --> 23:17.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the system.

23:17.533 --> 23:20.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And when you lose that
buttressing force,
you allow the upstream
glaciers to flow faster.

23:20.700 --> 23:24.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So that's similar to putting
more ice cubes into the
glass and letting those melt.

23:24.933 --> 23:28.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Ice falls off the
edge of glaciers all the time.

23:28.700 --> 23:32.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It is part of a natural
process called calving.

23:32.733 --> 23:37.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kelly Brunt says it is important
to judge the size of the
piece that breaks off relative

23:39.066 --> 23:41.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to the size of the
glacier that is behind it.

23:41.333 --> 23:44.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She says your fingernails
offer a handy model.

23:44.633 --> 23:48.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KELLY BRUNT: If you break
your fingernail inside the
white part of your fingernail,

23:48.533 --> 23:50.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
you probably don't
think much of it.

23:50.733 --> 23:55.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you break it below the
white part, you put a Band-Aid
on it, you think about it and

23:55.333 --> 23:57.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you keep an eye on it.

23:57.000 --> 23:59.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
If you lose your whole
fingernail, I don't
know what happens.

23:59.333 --> 24:00.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's pretty catastrophic.

24:00.900 --> 24:03.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This represents losing
the whole fingernail.

24:03.333 --> 24:08.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Like so many
features in Antarctica,
the Larsen Ice Shelf
is named for a famous

24:08.900 --> 24:11.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
19th century explorer.

24:11.666 --> 24:16.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And it is disappearing,
section by section,
identified by letters.

24:17.533 --> 24:20.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
