the size of Rhode Island.

24:33.300 --> 24:38.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KELLY BRUNT: Losing this much
ice, losing ice that represents
roughly the state of Rhode

24:38.100 --> 24:42.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Island in a month-and-a-half,
just far exceeded
anybody's expectations
of what could happen

24:42.566 --> 24:44.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in the time scale
that it could happen.

24:44.600 --> 24:47.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So, it was kind
of like, we have to rethink
things here a little bit.

24:47.566 --> 24:49.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, this is a wakeup call.

24:49.033 --> 24:51.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KELLY BRUNT: This was
absolutely a wakeup call.

24:51.433 --> 24:56.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Scientists track
the ice using a half-dozen
U.S. and European satellites,

24:57.600 --> 25:01.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
including Landsat, which
gathered these images.

25:01.033 --> 25:04.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But some of their best data came
from a satellite called ICESat.

25:04.933 --> 25:09.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Launched in 2003, it
ceased operation in 2009.

25:11.366 --> 25:13.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It precisely measured the
glaciers using laser beams.

25:13.800 --> 25:18.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KELLY BRUNT: This is quite
a few years of ICESat data
merged together to get a sense

25:20.200 --> 25:23.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in meters per year how
our ice sheet is changing.

25:23.266 --> 25:27.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you can see, the big picture
here is that our ice sheets
are changing where they are

25:27.033 --> 25:30.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in contact with both our warming
atmosphere and a warming ocean.

25:30.733 --> 25:33.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it's basically along
the fringe of the continent.

25:33.366 --> 25:38.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: When ICESat
failed, NASA started
tracking the ice using
radar and lasers on

25:39.466 --> 25:42.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
board low-flying aircraft.

25:42.500 --> 25:47.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The IceBridge program is NASA's
largest air campaign ever,
but it still could not match

25:48.233 --> 25:51.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the eye above the sky.

25:51.300 --> 25:54.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It goes without saying that you
would view these satellites,
the capability to look at

25:54.633 --> 25:56.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this, as essential?

25:56.666 --> 26:00.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KELLY BRUNT: What we're talking
about is a calving of an iceberg
that's a size of a state.

26:00.433 --> 26:05.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To get that, you really need
a satellite to be able to
see all of it in one shot.

26:05.266 --> 26:10.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a function of scale and
repeatability to go back and
look at that area again with

26:12.266 --> 26:15.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the satellite that makes these
the perfect tools for looking
at the large-scale change

26:15.033 --> 26:17.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that we're seeing
in this region.

26:17.500 --> 26:21.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: And that's
precisely what Kelly
Brunt and her colleagues
will be doing now,

26:21.400 --> 26:26.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
