from the scant weather stations
that are on the surface there,

26:27.833 --> 26:30.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and additionally with buoys
which are in the water itself.

26:30.833 --> 26:35.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They will be poring over this
data over the course of actually
years to try to make some

26:37.866 --> 26:40.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sort of definitive statement
-- and I put definitive in
quotes because it's science,

26:40.600 --> 26:45.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
after all -- as to whether
this particular calving event
is linked to climate change

26:46.200 --> 26:48.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
- - Judy.

26:48.200 --> 26:49.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, is
there a definitive answer
to that at this point?

26:49.900 --> 26:51.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It sounds like you're saying no.

26:51.166 --> 26:53.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Not just yet.

26:53.266 --> 26:55.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Here's what we know.

26:55.300 --> 26:58.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Larsen B, the previous big
calving event, scientists say
there is a very strong pile

26:58.933 --> 27:02.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
