practically no data at all.

27:05.133 --> 27:10.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it's one of these things
that, as Kelly Brunt put it,
this is where it gets exciting

27:11.266 --> 27:13.233 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for scientists.

27:13.233 --> 27:16.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They will try to determine
if it's climate change that
actually caused this to happen,

27:16.200 --> 27:20.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and also they will be
looking at the stability
of the ice shelf behind it.

27:20.633 --> 27:22.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Does the flow increase?

27:22.300 --> 27:26.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What about the glacier
behind the ice shelf itself?

27:26.033 --> 27:29.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Looking at all that will give
them a lot of clues about what
this is going to mean ultimately

27:29.566 --> 27:31.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for sea level rise.

27:31.666 --> 27:35.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And speaking of
that, do they know the effect
this is going to have on sea

27:36.933 --> 27:39.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
levels in the area
and around the world?

27:39.133 --> 27:41.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes,
that's the big question.

27:41.266 --> 27:45.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Larsen C, even though
it's called a shelf,
it's kind of misleading.

27:45.000 --> 27:47.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was already in the water.

27:47.066 --> 27:51.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so like an ice cube in a
glass of water, it had already
done its bit of displacement

27:51.333 --> 27:54.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and already had made its
impact on sea level rise.

27:54.233 --> 27:58.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If it had fallen off, scientists
estimate it would have
increased sea level across the

27:58.666 --> 28:00.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
world by three millimeters.

28:00.733 --> 28:02.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That the gives you the
idea of the size of this.

28:02.833 --> 28:07.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, now the situation here is
to see whether the increased
rate, if there's an increased

28:09.666 --> 28:13.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rate in the flow of that ice
shelf into the water, what
impact that might have on sea

28:14.433 --> 28:16.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
level rise in coming years.

28:16.433 --> 28:19.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, again, Judy, this is
long-term science, and we will
just have to watch it for years

28:19.900 --> 28:22.266 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to come.

28:22.266 --> 28:24.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, finally,
Miles, what happens
to this gigantic piece
of ice now that it's

28:24.666 --> 28:26.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
broken off?

28:26.633 --> 28:29.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, it
will probably not stay
intact the size of Delaware.

28:29.500 --> 28:31.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It will break up over time.

28:31.700 --> 28:36.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fortunately, where it is,
it's not going to be in the
way of any shipping channels.

28:36.033 --> 28:40.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So it shouldn't be a hazard
to navigation, but that's a
big part of what is going to

28:40.033 --> 28:42.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
happen along with
the other research.

28:42.166 --> 28:45.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They will be tracking to see
how this iceberg breaks up.

28:45.233 --> 28:50.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it will be a big
iceberg to start, and over
time it will get smaller.

28:50.066 --> 28:55.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right,
our iceberg man, Miles
O'Brien, thank you very much.

28:56.200 --> 29:01.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN:
You're welcome, Judy.

29:04.200 --> 29:09.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now we
continue our series
Inside Putin's Russia, and
travel to the country's

29:12.500 --> 29:14.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
southernmost border.

29:14.533 --> 29:18.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Republic of Dagestan
is in the North Caucasus,
near the Caspian Sea.

29:18.266 --> 29:23.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over the past two decades, a
brutal separatist insurgency has
fought the Russian state, and

29:25.200 --> 29:29.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
violence has spilled over
from neighboring Chechnya,
where Russia fought two wars.

29:31.366 --> 29:35.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many Americans may recall
Dagestan as the original home
of the Boston Marathon bombers,

29:36.100 --> 29:37.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
but now a new problem.

29:37.800 --> 29:42.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
By one estimate, as
many as 5,000 Dagestanis
are fighting for ISIS.

29:44.733 --> 29:47.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Again, in partnership with
the Pulitzer Center on Crisis
Reporting, special correspondent

29:49.300 --> 29:52.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Nick Schifrin and producer
Zach Fannin examine why.

29:52.500 --> 29:57.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAZIM NURMAGOMETOV, Russia: It
is no accident that the youth
are tempted to go to Syria,

30:01.766 --> 30:05.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
because, today, there
is a revival of Islam.

30:05.233 --> 30:10.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Kazim
Nurmagometov is 62 years old,
and his son fought for ISIS.

30:12.266 --> 30:15.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was never tempted to go to
Syria, but he and his wife,
Rashida, understand why their

30:15.833 --> 30:17.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
son, Marat, was.

30:17.900 --> 30:20.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAZIM NURMAGOMETOV (through
translator): The Islamic call
I was talking about, the one

30:20.566 --> 30:23.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in every Muslim's soul,
is hidden deep down.

30:23.633 --> 30:26.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's like a light
in someone's heart.

30:26.033 --> 30:30.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Nurmagometov
lives deep in the Caucasus
Mountains, where nearly dried-up

30:30.300 --> 30:35.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
rivers meander through
1,000-foot-high cliffs,
and beyond ancient rock
formations, isolated

30:36.533 --> 30:39.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
dirt roads connect
secluded villages.

30:39.766 --> 30:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
One of those villages is Karata.

30:41.733 --> 30:46.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Official population is
4,000, but residents
say it's half that size.

30:47.966 --> 30:50.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This area is nearly
100 percent Muslim.

30:50.433 --> 30:53.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Before Friday prayers,
men greet each other in
the small town center.

30:53.833 --> 30:57.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are few young people, in
part because this small village
sent as many as two dozen

30:57.666 --> 31:01.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to ISIS, al-Qaida, and the
wars in Syria and Iraq.

31:01.233 --> 31:02.233 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's her?

31:02.233 --> 31:03.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's your daughter.

31:03.733 --> 31:05.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AMINA KONDAKOVA, Russia
(through translator): Yes.

31:05.100 --> 31:06.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Amina
Kondakova is a Muslim convert.

31:06.366 --> 31:07.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She shows me photos
from a happier time.

31:07.900 --> 31:09.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's very cute.

31:09.333 --> 31:11.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She says they grew up
traditional and comfortable.

31:11.633 --> 31:15.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, two years ago, her
daughter Miryam and her son
Ali Askhat told her they were

31:15.400 --> 31:17.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
going on vacation.

31:17.433 --> 31:20.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Instead, they traveled
with Miriam's husband to
Mosul, Iraq, to join ISIS.

31:20.700 --> 31:23.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
AMINA KONDAKOVA (through
translator): They lied
to me about going there.

31:23.866 --> 31:25.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I was so disappointed.

31:25.400 --> 31:28.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then I became afraid about
what could happen to them.

31:28.266 --> 31:32.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NICK SCHIFRIN: She says
this town is pious,
but wasn't religious
enough for her daughter.

31:32.266 --> 31:36.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Did she feel judged by
people in this society?

31:36.400 --> 31:39.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
AMINA KONDAKOVA (through
translator): Yes,
they gave her looks.

31:39.433 --> 31:41.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They didn't like how
she was dressing.

31:41.200 --> 31:43.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They wanted her to dress
like everyone else.

31:43.500 --> 31:47.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
She wanted to dress to
way it's written for a
Muslim woman to dress.

31:47.033 --> 31:51.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Kondakova
believes that judgment
drove her daughter away.

31:51.466 --> 31:55.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She reluctantly admits that,
in Mosul, her daughter is happy
raising her first grandson.

31:55.566 --> 31:59.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMINA KONDAKOVA (through
translator): "Mom, I feel
like I was reborn here.

31:59.033 --> 32:01.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I regret all those years
I spent in Dagestan.

32:01.700 --> 32:03.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Don't you want to come here too?

32:03.233 --> 32:05.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I want to live with you, want
you to see my boy growing up."

32:05.666 --> 32:09.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Nurmagometov
gets to see his grandson.

32:09.833 --> 32:14.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
When his son Marat left
for Syria, he abandoned
a pregnant wife.

32:15.700 --> 32:17.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Alexey is now 3 years old.

32:17.766 --> 32:21.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They look at photos of Marat
as a boy, and a young Marat
clowning around with his older

32:21.666 --> 32:23.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
brother, Shamil.

32:23.633 --> 32:27.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When you look at these, does
it make you wish that your
sons could all be here with you

32:27.500 --> 32:29.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
together?

32:29.033 --> 32:30.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KAZIM NURMAGOMETOV (through
translator): I am a realist.

32:30.466 --> 32:32.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I know there's no return.

32:32.500 --> 32:36.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Life isn't a book where you
can tear out the pages if you
didn't like what you wrote, and

32:36.633 --> 32:38.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
write new ones.

32:38.700 --> 32:42.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: The Dagestanis
who fought for ISIS continue
a decades-old legacy here of

32:42.400 --> 32:44.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
radicalism and militancy.

32:44.400 --> 32:49.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's been a local insurgency
here in the capital of Dagestan,
Makhachkala, for years,

32:51.300 --> 32:54.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
targeting both local
authorities and symbols of
the national government.

32:54.633 --> 32:58.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their most prominent
attacks targeted civilians
in larger cities.

32:58.200 --> 33:02.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Moscow in 2010, militants
allied with al-Qaida
blew up the subway.

33:02.833 --> 33:07.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In 2013 in Volgograd, they blew
up a bus station, and then a
commuter bus, as seen on Russian

33:08.400 --> 33:10.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
media.

33:10.433 --> 33:13.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HABIB MAGOMEDOV, Former Police
Lieutenant Colonel (through
translator): There was no

33:13.400 --> 33:15.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
social or physical protection.

33:15.966 --> 33:20.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Every day, there were
bombings, terror attacks
that cost people's lives.

33:20.266 --> 33:24.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Habib Magomedov
is a former police lieutenant
colonel and member of Dagestan's

33:24.400 --> 33:26.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
anti-terrorism committee.

33:26.533 --> 33:31.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says conservative Islam,
combined with high rates of
unemployment and poverty, to

33:31.800 --> 33:34.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
radicalize.

33:34.300 --> 33:37.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HABIB MAGOMEDOV (through
translator): It's the
living conditions,
absence of possibilities,

33:39.033 --> 33:41.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
absence of social mobility,
which creates waves
of anger and distress.

33:41.133 --> 33:45.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There has to be some sort of
history that sets the person
on a certain track, where

33:45.433 --> 33:49.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you only need to light a
match for the fire to start.

33:49.200 --> 33:53.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
NICK SCHIFRIN: That
match is often a brutal
security crackdown.

33:53.633 --> 33:58.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
In January 2013, Russian
special forces flooded
into Dagestani villages.

34:00.733 --> 34:03.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Locals say security
services have practiced
collective punishment
against entire families,

34:03.366 --> 34:06.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
torture, even
extrajudicial executions.

34:06.833 --> 34:10.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Magomedov admits they went
too far, but he tries to
explain their motivation.

34:10.000 --> 34:14.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HABIB MAGOMEDOV (through
translator): If keeping
people safe requires
limiting rights and freedoms

34:14.800 --> 34:17.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of certain individuals,
it's probably worth it.

34:17.533 --> 34:21.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
My brother died in 1998
when someone threw a
grenade in his house.

34:21.733 --> 34:26.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, the freedom of
one man ends where the
freedom of another starts.

34:26.133 --> 34:30.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Today, the
violence has diminished.

34:30.133 --> 34:35.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's still religious
Muslims whose freedoms
are most often restricted.

34:36.566 --> 34:38.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This mosque practices an austere
and aggressive form of Islam.

34:38.566 --> 34:43.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It also rails against
government policy, and that
makes it a police target.

34:44.700 --> 34:47.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
After prayers, police
set up a checkpoint.

34:47.333 --> 34:51.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Officers must meet a
monthly quota of arrests,
leading to what many call
indiscriminate detentions,

34:52.966 --> 34:55.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
including of journalists trying
to tell the mosque's story.

34:55.600 --> 35:00.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We were filming that scene
from across the street, just
standing on the sidewalk for

35:00.200 --> 35:03.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
only about 90 seconds, when
police came up and arrested us.

35:03.466 --> 35:04.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They threw us into their car.

35:04.800 --> 35:06.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They drove us to the precinct.

35:06.266 --> 35:08.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They refused to tell us
why they were arresting us.

35:08.800 --> 35:11.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Why is he being arrested?

35:11.466 --> 35:16.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when we were in the station,
we saw dozens of men who had
been in that mosque before

35:16.166 --> 35:17.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
also arrested.

35:17.800 --> 35:19.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That is simply how
people here act.

35:19.533 --> 35:22.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Thirty-three-year-old
Mogamet Mogametov is
the mosque's spokesman.

35:22.533 --> 35:26.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MOGAMET MOGAMETOV, Mosque
Spokesman (through translator):
As you saw yourself, they arrest

35:26.766 --> 35:30.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people not because they're
suspicious, but only because
they came to a mosque.

35:30.600 --> 35:34.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Do you think
that the tactics that the police
use can help to radicalize

35:34.200 --> 35:35.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
young people here?

35:35.700 --> 35:37.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MOGAMET MOGAMETOV (through
translator): Of course.

35:37.533 --> 35:39.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This is the thing
that provokes people.

35:39.633 --> 35:43.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Since literally everyone can
be arrested, not on the basis
of actual cause, but something

35:43.933 --> 35:46.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
totally subjective, then
of course that irritates.

35:46.500 --> 35:49.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: And that
helped lead so many to ISIS.

35:49.966 --> 35:52.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The group exploits the abuse.

35:52.866 --> 35:57.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russian language propaganda says
Russia oppresses Muslims, and
presents Syria and Iraq as a

35:58.733 --> 36:00.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pious paradise fit for families.

36:00.900 --> 36:05.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And as ISIS recruited
Dagestanis, Russian
security services showed
some the door, exporting

36:07.066 --> 36:08.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
extremism by facilitating
their travel to Syria.

36:08.766 --> 36:12.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
HABIB MAGOMEDOV (through
translator): It was
the right thing to do.

36:12.600 --> 36:17.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Since the moment these people
left Dagestan for Syria, local
terrorism dropped dramatically.

36:17.400 --> 36:20.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If they had stayed, there
would have been terror attacks.

36:20.433 --> 36:21.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
There would have been
human casualties.

36:21.700 --> 36:23.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Who
helped you leave?

36:23.466 --> 36:25.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Who facilitated your departure?

36:25.733 --> 36:30.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of those who was pushed
is this 27-year-old Dagestani
who now lives in Turkey.

36:30.066 --> 36:33.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We agreed to hide his
face and alter his voice.

36:33.033 --> 36:37.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator):
People who were on the federal
wanted list could somehow get

36:37.233 --> 36:39.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a passport and
leave the country.

36:39.366 --> 36:42.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some security officers said to
them, we will either kill you
or you can leave the country.

36:42.800 --> 36:46.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The way I was helped was that
every time I went to my local
government office, I was

36:46.666 --> 36:48.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
taken by the police
and interrogated.

36:48.300 --> 36:50.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But when I went to get a
passport, nobody stopped me.

36:50.800 --> 36:55.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: And after the
Dagestanis left, Russia made
sure they never came back.

36:55.166 --> 36:59.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): They
simply said that, if I come
back, they will do bad things

36:59.033 --> 37:00.100 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to me.

37:00.100 --> 37:02.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So I won't ever go back.

37:02.166 --> 37:06.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Many Dagestanis
who fought for ISIS have died
in Syria, and they're celebrated

37:06.133 --> 37:09.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
by ISIS propaganda.

37:09.166 --> 37:13.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But some managed to
escape, often to the port
city of Odessa, Ukraine.

37:13.866 --> 37:17.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Former ISIS fighter Marat
agreed to talk to us if
we didn't show his face.

37:17.266 --> 37:20.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARAT, Former ISIS Fighter
(through translator):
The majority went to
Syria with the notion

37:20.066 --> 37:23.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of jihad, that Assad was
repressing Muslims and
we needed to help them.

37:23.400 --> 37:26.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: We have
actually already met Marat.

37:26.700 --> 37:29.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He's the son of
Kazim Nurmagometov.

37:29.000 --> 37:30.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Kazim is often in
Odessa to visit.

37:30.966 --> 37:34.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAZIM NURMAGOMETOV
(through translator): We
consider our family lucky.

37:34.833 --> 37:39.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He is back, alive and healthy,
and realized that where he
ended up wasn't what he thought

37:39.266 --> 37:41.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it was.

37:41.366 --> 37:44.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: When his son
left for Syria, Kazim didn't
sit back and let him die.

37:44.266 --> 37:47.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He traveled to the outskirts of
Aleppo and saw the destruction.

37:47.600 --> 37:50.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He helped convince
Marat he made a mistake.

37:50.000 --> 37:53.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Marat finally left when he
thought about his own son.

37:53.400 --> 37:56.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARAT (through translator):
I was thinking about him
constantly, hoping that I could

37:56.633 --> 37:58.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
leave and see my child.

37:58.133 --> 38:00.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I was always thinking about
what a big mistake I made.

